 for party democracy. The book presents evidence of a desire for change in party ethos, introducing the idea of the re-imagined party to explore perceptions of party representation, participation, governance and conduct. Using a mixed-method approach, and presenting hitherto unseen data, the book casts new light on citizen’s desires for parties today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical partieszGreat BritainxPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionzGreat Britain. 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh  aDemocratic linkage.  aMixed-methods.  aParty adaptation.  aParty conduct.  aPolitical parties.  aPublic desires.  aPublic perceptions.  aRe-imagined Party.  aRepresentation.  aUnited Kingdom.1 aDommett, Katharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615025740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526150257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526150257/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles